    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-02-14T23:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-02-14T23:00:00-05:00" n="648"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d648">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.5151/987: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-02-15T11:00:00+07:00"
                            >February 15, 1944—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 1:53 p.m. |</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>305. To Secretary of Treasury from Adler. Kung has asked me to transmit following
                    addendum to the message sent in my 252, February 8.</p>
                <pb facs="0887" n="873" xml:id="pg_873"/>
                <quote rend="blockquote">
                    <p>“Attention was brought, in the first paragraph of my previous message, to the
                        rise in the U. S. dollar currency black market rate, which was caused in
                        part by the rumor that America is asking for reduction in the official
                        exchange rate.</p>
                    <p>The position has since considerably deteriorated, transactions having
                        occurred at rates up to 195; naturally, this increase impairs confidence
                        with the diffusion of the impression that the rate will be reduced and we
                        may anticipate its contributing further to the rise in prices. I desire to
                        call the circumstances to your attention so that in your consideration of
                        current questions you may be guided accordingly.”</p>
                </quote>
                <p>Above paraphrase. [Adler.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
